How do You Deal with Uncertainty?¶

Suppose some dark night a policeman walks down a street, apparently deserted. Suddenly he hears a burglar alarm, looks across the street, and sees a jewelry store with a broken window. Then a gentleman wearing a mask comes crawling out through the broken window, carrying a bag which turns out to be full of expensive jewelry. The policeman doesn’t hesitate at all in deciding that this gentleman is dishonest. But by what reasoning process does he arrive at this conclusion?

Questions you should ask:¶

  • Was the policeman’s conclusion a logical deduction from the evidence?
  • The gentleman could have been the owner of the jewelry store and he was coming home from a masquerade party, and didn’t have the key with him. However, just as he walked by his store, a passing truck threw a stone through the window, and he was only protecting his own property.

Logical Reasoning¶

A ↔↔ "it will start to rain by 10 am at the latest"

B ↔↔ "the sky will become cloudy before 10 am"

Which of the following is correct?

  • A⇒⇒B (If A is true, then B is true)
  • B⇒⇒A (If B is true, then A is true)

Plausible Reasoning¶

Which of the following is correct?

  • If A is true, then B becomes more plausible
  • If B is true, then A becomes more plausible

Sound Human Reasoning¶

  • Human reasoning depends on prior information to evaluate the degree of plausibility in a new problem.
  • This reasoning process goes on unconsciously.
  • This is what you common sense.
  • The key steps are:
    • observed data →→ form a hypothesis (based on prior beliefs) →→ updated your beliefs based on new evidence
